title: U-233 fission cross section measured using a nuclear explosion in space.

x4codes.hlp: Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore, CA, United States of America

x4freetext: U-233 fission cross section measured using a nuclear
explosion in space.
A high-altitude nuclear explosion in 1962 was
used as a neutron source in an experiment to measure
the fission cross section of U233 relative to U235 in
the 30-eV to 5-MeV energy region.
Each fission counter was constructed entirely
of aluminum in the form of concentric cylinders on
which uranium was chemically plated to a depth of
about 200 mu-g/cm2. The fission counters were 3 in.
in diam. and 1.5 in. long. They were filled to a
pressure of about 80 lb/in. with gas composed of 96%
argon and 4% carbon dioxide, and had operating
plateaus in the region of 500 V.

relative to the U-235 cross section was calculated
from the ratio of the counting rates of the U-233 and
U-235 fission chambers obtained from the experiment.
